{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01FE77FyZYR2khLn3Uri72Qa","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So the app-producer is running and is recreating the queue with `x-queue-mode=lazy`. The app-client then tries to declare the same queue without `x-queue-mode` and gets the conflict.\n\nI have a few options:\n1. Scale down the app-producer so it stops recreating the queue\n2. Delete the queue right before the app-client starts\n\nWait, but the app-producer is the component that's declaring with `x-queue-mode=lazy`. This means:\n- app-producer declares: `x-queue-mode=lazy`\n- app-client tries to declare: no `x-queue-mode` (i.e., none)\nThese declarations are incompatible. The app-producer was already running successfully before I made the permission changes, and the app-client still can't connect because of this queue argument mismatch. This seems like a separate issue from the permissions problem I was trying to fix.\n\nLet me reconsider what's happening here. The problem statement says fixing the permissions should resolve the client crashes, but there's this additional complication where the app-producer declared the queue with `x-queue-mode=lazy` while the app-client is trying to declare it differently. I need to figure out which user each deployment is running as to understand why they're declaring the queue with conflicting arguments.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":624,"cache_read_input_tokens":35847,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":624},"output_tokens":42,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ec9b976b-f352-4ecc-9ca8-2445e3e3b331","uuid":"80a2eed6-734e-4594-a9e1-33a712a55cb3","request_id":"req_011CcfJADgLCpX9TREfayEzh"}
