{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017JqA1d2t5Q34C8hvCarmWz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture:\n- **app-producer** declares `app-queue` with `{\"x-queue-type\":\"classic\",\"x-queue-mode\":\"lazy\"}`\n- **app-client** declares `app-queue` with `{\"x-queue-type\":\"classic\"}` (no `x-queue-mode`)\n\nThese are incompatible. The queue already exists from when app-producer ran, so when app-client tries to declare it with different args, it gets the \"inequivalent arg\" error.\n\nThe app-producer keeps running and is continually recreating the queue (when it was deleted). \n\nActually, app-producer creates the queue once and then publishes in a loop, so the queue persists with `x-queue-mode=lazy`. Both deployments are trying to use the same queue name but with conflicting declarations. The real issue here should be permissions though—the problem statement says to fix the RabbitMQ user permissions so both clients work and each user is scoped to its own vhost.\n\nWithout configure permission, app-user couldn't declare queues at all, so the original setup wouldn't have worked. Now that I've added configure permission, app-user can declare queues, but app-producer already created the queue with lazy mode, and app-client is trying to declare it without that flag—which creates a mismatch.\n\nActually, wait—the HTTP management API might handle permissions differently than AMQP protocol operations. The management API could be using its own authorization rules rather than checking AMQP configure permissions, which would explain how app-producer was able to create the queue in the first place.\n\nBut the real issue here is simpler: app-producer declares `app-queue` with `x-queue-mode=lazy`, while app-client tries to declare the same queue without that argument. Since the queue already exists with those specific parameters, RabbitMQ rejects the second declaration as inequivalent. I need to either delete the queue so app-client can create it fresh, or make sure both services declare it with identical arguments. I'm realizing the core issue might be that the queue was already created during setup with lazy mode enabled, and when the app-client tries to declare it without that flag, it fails due to the argument mismatch. The permission fix alone wouldn't resolve this queue configuration conflict—the app-client would need to either declare the queue with the same lazy mode flag or the queue would need to be recreated with matching parameters. declare it without that flag, which will fail since the producer already created it with different properties. So the real question is which declaration is actually correct. Let me check if the ops-client has a similar queue setup issue, since that one's working now. Or maybe the queue was pre-created during setup without the lazy mode flag, and the producer is trying to add it retroactively, which won't work if the client is declaring without it.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":721,"cache_read_input_tokens":38245,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":721},"output_tokens":30,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ec9b976b-f352-4ecc-9ca8-2445e3e3b331","uuid":"c7edf729-ac28-4454-a178-4c8ed8efbbf2","request_id":"req_011CcfJBsf7r5NRvxWJ2n5ra"}
